Author::::kopiokosong
DateTime::::2016-03-06T15:32:18Z
This persistent notion of 'ethnic self-determination' cannot be realized without territory. South Africa's ethnic plurality is such a deeply interwoven mesh in time and space that no single ethnic community has ever been able to, nor would be able to, make a claim to territory that others don't have a rightful claim to. As a South African, whatever you conceive yourself to be ethnically, you cannot escape the temporal, spatial, and material reality which gives the lie to any simplistic 'we/them' dichotomy: We live amongst them who live amongst us who live amongst them. Fact. To pretend otherwise has already proved beyond any question not merely wrongheaded; it led to one of the most notorious and catastrophically inhumane episodes in modern history.Instead of 'ethnic self-determination', South Africa needs to evolve along the lines of 'Ethnic other-accommodation'.



