Author::::philemondaba
DateTime::::2016-03-06T11:07:04Z
According to article 235 of the South African constitution, it permits, embraces and protects ethnic, linguistic, cultural and religious self-determination. This same self-determination, which you label as ludicrous, was deemed so important that it is set out in article 1 of the United Nations charter - the very existance of nations is segregation, despite leftist hatred of real ethnic, linguistic and cultural diversity. Furthermore, its predecessor, the League of Nations, included the self same concept in its covenant, in Article 22. These precepts were used, in international law, to establish Namibia, in its current context, as well as for the reunification of Germany, amongst many other important world events. UNPO, the organisation representing the unrepresented, is widely made up of African nations without their own political power, of which the Afrikaner is but one. Just because you happen to find self-determination an anachronism, does not invalidate it, nor does it conflate it with the political system that was Apartheid. I may not know everything, as you seem to, but I certainly know my way around a legal text. I conclude, the only way we will ever improve in Africa is if we embrace "good neighbourlyness" separately. I can no more write the rules for a Tshwana or a Venda, than they can for me or for each other.



